<hint name="helpSection"><title>Worked Example</title>
  
<p>Here is a similar worked example:</p> 
<example newNamespace>

<setup>
  <math name="a">8</math>
  <math name="b">3</math>
  <math name="expr">e^(x + $a) = e^x + $b</math>
  <math name="sol">ln($b/(e^($a) - 1))</math>
</setup>


<!--testing-->
<!-- <p>a = $a</p>
<p>b = $b</p>
<p>c = $c</p>
<p>sol = $sol</p> -->
<!--testing-->

<p>Find the solution of the exponential equation
<me>$expr</me></p>

<p><em><alert>Solution.</alert></em></p>
<p>First, we need to simplify and combine terms, with the goal of having only a single exponential term on one side of the equation. Only then can we take the natural log of both sides to isolate the <m>x</m>.
    <md>
      <mrow>e^{x + $a} \amp= e^x + $b </mrow>
      <mrow>e^{x + $a} - e^x \amp= $b  \quad\quad\text{get all terms involving}\; x \;\text{on the left}</mrow>
      <mrow>e^{x}\cdot e^{$a} - e^x \amp= $b \quad\quad\text{use properties of exponents to separate the}\; (x + $a) \;\text{term}</mrow>
      <mrow>e^{x} (e^{$a} - 1) \amp= $b \quad\quad\text{factor out an} \;e^x</mrow>
      <mrow>e^{x} \amp= \frac{$b}{(e^{$a} - 1 )} \quad\quad\text{isolate}\;e^x</mrow>
      <mrow>\ln (e^{x}) \amp= \ln \bigg(\frac{$b}{e^{$a} - 1 }\bigg) \quad\quad\text{take the natural log of both sides}</mrow>
      <mrow>x \amp= \ln \bigg(\frac{$b}{e^{$a} - 1 }\bigg) \quad\quad\text{simplify}</mrow>
    </md>
You can leave your answer in this format: <m>x = $sol</m>, or use a calculator to get a decimal approximation for <m>x</m>:
  <me>x \approx <number displayDecimals="4">$sol</number></me>
  
</p>
</example>


 </hint>
  

<!--*********************************************
            Solution
**********************************************-->
<solution>
<p><m>x = $sol</m>, or <m>x \approx <number displayDecimals="4">$sol</number></m></p>
</solution>
</problem>

